  "opinion": "As a 22-year-old woman in Rome studying for a bachelor's degree, I've experienced stereotype threat firsthand in STEM fields. Growing up in a household where my father had no formal education and my mother only completed lower secondary school, I've always felt the weight of expectations that my gender and background might limit my potential in technical subjects. Stereotype threat isn't just a theoretical concept—it's the anxiety that comes when you're aware of negative stereotypes about your group, which can impair your performance. In my physics class last semester, I noticed how my male classmates seemed more confident when discussing complex problems, while I often hesitated, worrying that my 'lack of math skills' (a stereotype I've internalized) might be a sign of inadequacy. This isn't just about individual performance; it's about systemic issues that affect how we learn and grow. Should we address it? Absolutely. But the approach needs to be nuanced. Schools and universities must create environments where students feel safe to make mistakes without fear of judgment. For me, this means having open conversations about stereotypes in class, where teachers acknowledge that everyone starts at different points and that anxiety about being perceived as 'less capable' can be a real barrier. My high neuroticism score makes me particularly sensitive to this, but it's also what drives me to seek understanding and solutions. How can we do this effectively? By integrating implicit bias training for educators, creating mentorship programs that connect students with role models who share their backgrounds, and designing curricula that highlight diverse contributions to STEM. In Rome, where I live, we have a strong tradition of community support, so building on that could help dismantle these barriers. It's not just about fixing the problem—it's about creating a space where every student, regardless of their background, feels valued and capable. I believe that when we address stereotype threat head-on, we don't just improve academic outcomes; we build a more inclusive and equitable future for everyone.",
